From December 31 2024, Australian organisations are required to report on the climate change risks and opportunities across the value chain of their organisation.  This is described in the Australian Sustainability Reporting Standard AASB S2: https://standards.aasb.gov.au/aasb-s2-sep-2024

"This Standard, when applicable, requires an entity to disclose information about climate-related risks and opportunities that could reasonably be expected to affect the entityâ€™s cash flows, its access to finance or cost of capital over the short, medium or long term."

The standard contains three groups for reporting:
Scope 1: Greenhouse gas emissions directly generated by the organisation.
Scope 2: Indirect greenhouse gas emissions resulting from the generation of power consumed by the organisation.
Scope 3: Other greenhouse gas emissions across the value chain of the organisation.

Reporting of the Greenhouse Gas Emissions resulting from employee commuting is covered under Scope 3.  

Employee commuting avoided due to WFH creates big win for organisations through the avoidance of greenhouse gas emissions.  This benefit increases with distance travelled, and can be substantial where the employee commutes from outside of the metropolitan area.  A WFH log is also required by the employee in order to claim WFH tax benefits (two birds with one stone).

